er I need to include test resources in alternate classes or if child JVM processes could work with a different classpath. If I use a custom ClassLoader to load classes from byte arrays, then I might employ reflection to access public APIs. However, I'm cautious about using reflection unless it’s truly necessary, as it can be a dubious approach.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class definitions**\\n\\nI’m trying to wrap my head around the challenge of defining the same binary class twice. It seems that I could use a custom child-first loader to define JmDNSV1 bytes from a resource, but I'd need the class bytes for v1 with the same name. There’s the option of incorporating JavaCompiler for dynamic class loading, but that might get too complicated and unsupported by native. \\n\\nIt feels like I'm figuring out how to navigate these limitations without using reflection or Unsafe, which would just complicate things further.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing class configurations**\\n\\nI'm looking into setting jmDNSClass to a class without a constructor and serviceInfoClass to one with a constructor. I wonder if I need to call private fields through VarHandle since direct reflection isn't an option. Maybe I could add a helper in the org.apache.log4j.net package, but private fields are still inaccessible. \\n\\nI’m considering whether to handle an optional dependency with version 1 and 3 variants and if test resolution can run multiple times. It seems likely I'll edit to version 1, but I'm pondering whether maintaining version 3 coverage is really necessary.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting compiler utility**\\n\\nI’m thinking about what to do if the compiler is null. I wonder if I could assert it maybe isn’t that big of a deal. In the native context, I’m considering that getSystemJavaCompiler could also be null, which might lead to an AssertionError, and that's not permitted. There might be a utility in NativeIm